objective:
The challenge to be addressed by the SIGMA project is to deploy alert systems that can restore the integrity of GNSS systems, meaning the system's ability to provide valid indicators allowing end-users to decide when the system should not be used for the intended operation, including in the event of external and voluntary interference with the GNSS system itself.

In this framework, SIGMA consortium proposes to investigate technologies and concepts that will detect, localise and analyse radiofrequency sources that would be operating at the Earth surface level with the aim to disrupt GNSS devices. These innovative solutions will be based on satellite platforms operating at low or very low altitudes and that will be equipped with acquisition and processing payloads dedicated to GNSS jamming and spoofing analysis. This orbital deployment will offer global coverage and great flexibility compared to the implementation of ground-based means which require slow, costly, and complex infrastructures to be deployed. The service provided by this type of system to end-users will consist of mapping the positions of sources of GNSS interferences, with this map being frequently updated as the satellite passes overhead. The benefit for users will be knowing the level of confidence and integrity characterizing their satellite positioning system at any time. The system will also define the characteristics of the detected spoofing actions, allowing these positioning systems to isolate the sources of interference, to implement counter-measures, and thus to restore an acceptable level of performance and availability of the service.

The SIGMA project will therefore contribute to the development, and to the operational and functional validation, of a GNSS signal monitoring solution. This asset will measure the integrity of GNSS service by using satellite platforms orbiting at low altitudes (around 300-400 km). This task will be performed by analysing signals originating from the Earth's surface. The system will scan the Earth's surface using a sensitive multi-element antenna (like CRPA-type antennas, Controlled Radiation Pattern Antennas), the final deliverable being the map of all detected radio-interference sources.

The objective of the SIGMA project is therefore to conduct a demonstration in a real-world environment of monitoring and surveillance methods for critical electronic systems, specifically GNSS positioning systems, based on satellite platforms operating in orbit. In this context, the project will include the following tasks:

• Development of a software/hardware payload for GNSS signal analysis to be implemented by the French partner M3 systems;
• Development of a satellite and integration of the payload onto this platform to be realized by the Bulgarian partner Endurosat;
• Implementation of a system for retrieving pre-processed data on the ground using an innovative and flexible encryption solution to secure the data link, to be performed by the Estonian partner Skudo;
• Deployment of the satellite and its payload into low Earth orbit on a trajectory representative of the case studies, to be done by the French partner Latitude.

Finally, the project will cover the experimental operation of the entire system, including the acquisition and processing of GNSS signals, which will ideally be representative of spoofing and jamming situations. To capture relevant signals, overflights of conflict zones will be included in the flight plan.
